sly published papers written by distinguished comparative law scholars. The authors investigate whether the common law trust could be understood as a civil law patrimony by appropriation, and whether civil law and mixed traditions could create local versions of the common law trust using patrimony as the main conceptual building block. Key FeaturesThe first comparative law book addressing the relation between trust and patrimony from a comparative and trans-systemic perspectiveFocusses on the private law of England, Scotland, Quebec and the NetherlandsResponds to the increasing appeal and popularity of the institution of trust in civil law jurisdictions in Continental Europe and AsiaAn invaluable resource for legal researchers, practitioners and policy makers interested in the theoretical and practical challenges that the trust poses in civil law countries  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aTrusts and trustees. 4aLaw. 7aLAW / Comparative.2bisacsh1 aGretton, George L, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKasirer, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthews, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPopovici, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Kenneth G C, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmieman, Emile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Lionel D, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValsan, Remus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311078045140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748697755423Coveruhttps://www.degr